texts.value: Catalyzes the peptide bond hydrolysis in dipeptides, displaying a non-redundant activity toward threonyl dipeptides (By similarity). Mediates threonyl dipeptide catabolism in a tissue-specific way (By similarity). Has high dipeptidase activity toward cysteinylglycine, an intermediate metabolite in glutathione metabolism (PubMed:19346245, PubMed:12473676). Metabolizes N-lactoyl-amino acids, both through hydrolysis to form lactic acid and amino acids, as well as through their formation by reverse proteolysis (PubMed:25964343). Plays a role in the regulation of cell cycle arrest and apoptosis (PubMed:17121880, PubMed:24395568)

reaction.name: Hydrolysis of dipeptides, preferentially hydrophobic dipeptides including prolyl amino acids.

texts.value: Inhibited by p-hydroxymercurybenzoate. The inhibitory concentration 50% (IC(50)) is 13 uM. Inhibited by bestatin. The inhibitory concentration 50% (IC(50)) is 7 nM at pH 9.5

michaelisConstants.substrate: L-serylglutamine (at pH 7.5 and in the presence of 0.1 mM manganese ions)
L-cysteinylglycine (at pH 8.0 and in the presence of 50 uM manganese ions)
carnosine (at pH 9.5 and in the presence of 0.1 mM manganese ions)

texts.value: Ubiquitously expressed with higher levels in kidney and liver (at protein level). Expressed in peripheral blood leukocytes (PubMed:12473676). Expressed in gastric mucosa and down-regulated in gastric cancer mucosal tissues (at protein level) (PubMed:24395568)
Broadly expressed in fetal tissues. Expressed in adult liver and placenta

The reverse proteolysis is not negligible in vivo as long as the substrates are present in considerable concentrations, such as upon physical exercice. N-lac-Phe plasma levels are increased in patients with PKU with increased plasma Phe levels. N-lactoyl-amino acids are present in many tissues
Lacks a part of the catalytic domain
Belongs to the peptidase M20A family
